And now, dear friends, here's John Rovaki.

01:10.440 --> 01:15.360
You have an excellent 50 part lecture series online on the Meaning Crisis.

01:15.960 --> 01:21.880
And I think you describe in the modern times an increase in depression, loneliness,

01:21.920 --> 01:26.080
cynicism and wait for it bullshit.

01:26.640 --> 01:30.680
The term used technically by Harry Frankfurt and adopted by you.

01:30.680 --> 01:33.160
So let me ask, what is meaning?

01:33.800 --> 01:40.000
What are we looking for when we engage in the search for meaning?

01:40.200 --> 01:43.440
So when I'm talking about meaning, I'm talking about what's called meaning in life,

01:43.560 --> 01:45.040
not the meaning of life.

01:45.080 --> 01:46.760
That's some sort of metaphysical claim.

01:47.400 --> 01:51.960
Meaning in life are those factors that make people rate their lives as more

01:51.960 --> 01:55.080
meaningful, worth living, worth the suffering that they have to endure.

01:55.880 --> 02:01.880
And when you study that, what you see is it's a sense of connectedness,

02:03.160 --> 02:07.880
connectedness to yourself, to other people, to the world and a particular

02:07.880 --> 02:09.280
kind of connectedness.

02:09.880 --> 02:14.960
You want to be connected to things that have a value and an existence

02:14.960 --> 02:19.080
independent of your egocentric sort of preferences and concerns.

02:19.120 --> 02:22.240
This is why, for example, having a child is considered very meaningful because

02:22.240 --> 02:26.040
you're connecting to something that's going to have a life and a value

02:26.040 --> 02:27.880
independent of you.

02:28.960 --> 02:33.360
Now, the question that comes up for me, well, there's two questions.

02:33.360 --> 02:35.960
One is, why is that at risk right now?

02:36.520 --> 02:41.080
And then secondly, and I think you have to answer the second question first,

02:41.080 --> 02:44.040
which is, well, yeah, but why is meaning so important?

02:44.040 --> 02:46.600
Why is this sense of connectedness so important to human beings?

02:46.600 --> 02:51.040
Why, when it is lacking, do they typically fall into depression,

02:51.040 --> 02:54.520
potentially mental illness, addiction, self-destructive behavior?

02:55.040 --> 02:59.200
And so the first answer I give you is, well, it's that sense of connectedness.

02:59.440 --> 03:01.200
And people often express it metaphorically.

03:01.200 --> 03:03.760
They want to be connected to something larger than themselves.

03:03.760 --> 03:04.600
They want to matter.

03:05.040 --> 03:06.200
They don't mean it literally.

03:06.600 --> 03:10.240
I mean, if I chained you to a mountain, you wouldn't thereby say, oh, now my life

03:10.240 --> 03:11.560
is so fulfilling, right?

03:12.000 --> 03:15.040
So what they're trying to convey, they're using this metaphor to try and say,

03:15.560 --> 03:16.600
they want to be connected.

03:17.240 --> 03:18.760
They want to be connected to something real.

03:19.080 --> 03:21.480
They want to make a difference and matter to it.

03:22.160 --> 03:27.920
And one way of asking them, well, you know, what's meaningful is tell me what

03:27.920 --> 03:31.600
you would like to continue to exist, even if you weren't around anymore.

03:32.520 --> 03:35.080
And how are you connected to it and how do you matter to it?

03:36.080 --> 03:44.360
That's one way of trying to get at what is the source of meaning for you is if

03:44.360 --> 03:47.720
you were no longer there, you would like it to continue existing.

03:48.560 --> 03:52.520
That's not the only part of the definition, probably, because there's

03:52.520 --> 03:58.480
probably many things that aren't a source of meaning for me that maybe I find

03:58.480 --> 04:01.800
beautiful, that I would like to continue existing.

04:01.800 --> 04:02.320
Yes.

04:02.760 --> 04:07.400
If it contributes to your life being meaningful, you're connected to it in

04:07.400 --> 04:14.560
some way, and it matters to you, and you matter to it in that you make some

04:14.560 --> 04:15.280
difference to it.

04:15.560 --> 04:19.240
That's when it goes from being just sort of true, good, and beautiful to being

04:19.240 --> 04:20.960
a source of meaning for you in your life.

04:21.920 --> 04:26.080
Is the meaning crisis a new thing, or has it always been with us?

04:26.080 --> 04:28.280
Is it part of the human condition in general?

04:28.920 --> 04:30.240
That's an excellent question.

04:30.600 --> 04:33.920
And part of the argument I made in Awakening for the Meaning Crisis is there's

04:33.920 --> 04:35.200
two aspects to it.

04:36.040 --> 04:41.040
One is that there are perennial problems, perennial threats to meaning.

04:42.400 --> 04:46.240
And in that sense, human beings are always vulnerable to despair.

04:46.240 --> 04:50.160
You know, the book of Ecclesiastes is, it's all vanity, it's all meaningless.

04:51.600 --> 04:57.440
But there's also historical forces that have made those perennial problems

04:58.000 --> 05:03.200
more pertinent, more pressing, more difficult for people to deal with.

05:03.200 --> 05:08.200
And so the meaning crisis is actually the intersection of perennial problems,

05:08.200 --> 05:12.960
finding existing, existence absurd, experiencing existential anxiety,

05:12.960 --> 05:17.680
feeling alienated, and then pressing historical factors, which have to do

05:17.680 --> 05:22.320
with the loss of the resources that human beings have typically crossed

05:22.320 --> 05:24.880
historically and cross-culturally made use of.

05:25.200 --> 05:30.960
Is there something potentially deeper than just a lack of meaning

05:30.960 --> 05:35.360
that speaks to the fact that we're vulnerable to despair?

05:35.360 --> 05:40.240
You know, Ernest Becker talked about the, in his book, The Nile of Death,

05:40.240 --> 05:44.880
about the fear of death and being an important motivator in our life.

05:44.880 --> 05:48.640
As William James said, death is the warm at the heart of life.

05:48.640 --> 05:51.120
Death is the warm at the heart of life.

05:51.120 --> 05:56.880
In our life, as William James said, death is the warm at the core of the human condition.

05:56.880 --> 06:06.240
Is it possible that this kind of search for meaning is coupled or can be seen

06:06.240 --> 06:13.920
from the perspective of trying to escape the reality, the thought of one's own mortality?

06:15.440 --> 06:19.040
Yeah, Becker and the terror management theory that have come out of it.

06:19.040 --> 06:24.000
There's been some good work around sort of providing empirical support for that claim.

06:26.560 --> 06:27.920
